## 2026-05-10 20:30:00 — SIGNED_BY_AGENT
Decision: Use Haiku (claude-haiku-4-5-20251001) as umbrella LLM for vox peer, preserving NATS
for all other nova agents.
Reason: Headless Claude Code (vox-agent.service) incurs 18-20s cold-start latency and delivers
non-streaming responses. Haiku via Anthropic streaming API achieves ~1-2s TTFT with token-level
streaming. For the default voice persona (vox), this eliminates the most user-perceptible delay.
Specialized agents (herald, tecton, iris, etc.) retain NATS routing unchanged — they have richer
context needs that justify the latency tradeoff.

Decision: Set endpointing=800ms in Deepgram listen provider.
Reason: Default Deepgram VAD endpointing was cutting Chase's turns mid-sentence at natural speech
pauses. 800ms gives enough silence headroom for typical intra-sentence pauses while keeping
turn-taking responsive. Configurable at the SettingsConfiguration level; adjustable per session
if needed.

## 2026-05-10 19:44:00 — SIGNED_BY_AGENT
Decision: Proxy Deepgram WS through gateway.py instead of connecting browser directly.
Reason: `/v1/auth/grant` tokens are scoped to `asr:write` only; the Voice Agent API
requires a full API key or a token with broader scope. Proxying keeps the key server-side,
eliminates the 30s token TTL problem, and gives us full visibility into the DG protocol for
future debugging.

## 2026-05-10 19:17:00 — SIGNED_BY_AGENT
Decision: Replace WebRTC+pipecat with Deepgram Voice Agent API.
Reason: WebRTC state is process-local (ICE, DTLS); any service restart drops the user mid-session.
Deepgram Voice Agent API handles STT/VAD/TTS server-side over a single browser WebSocket, eliminating
the pipecat pipeline and WebRTC entirely. No process-local media state means future gateway.py
restarts do not terminate voice sessions (browser reconnects to Deepgram directly).

Decision: Deepgram "think" endpoint = our /v1/chat/completions gateway (OpenAI SSE format).
Reason: Deepgram's agent calls any OpenAI-compatible completions endpoint. Our gateway extracts
the last user message, publishes to NATS, and streams chunks as SSE. This preserves the full
nova NATS routing layer unchanged — peer/channel selection via query params.

Decision: Live agent routing via SettingsConfiguration resend (not WS reconnect).
Reason: Deepgram accepts a new SettingsConfiguration at any time on the open WS connection, updating
the think endpoint URL in-flight. This means selectAgent() changes the NATS target with zero latency
and no audio interruption.

Decision: PCM capture via ScriptProcessor (not AudioWorklet).
Reason: iOS Safari support for AudioWorklet is incomplete as of 2026. ScriptProcessor is deprecated
but universally supported including iOS PWA. Nearest-neighbour downsample from actual sampleRate
(commonly 44.1kHz or 48kHz on iOS despite the 16kHz hint) to 16kHz is sufficient for speech.

Decision: 24kHz playback AudioContext shared across all TTS chunks (gapless chaining).
Reason: Creating a new AudioContext per TTS chunk causes gaps and "click" artifacts. A single
persistent context with `nextPlayTime` scheduling chains buffers without gaps.

## 2026-05-10 01:07:00 — SIGNED_BY_AGENT
Decision: Debounce TranscriptionFrames in NATSAgentProcessor (600ms) rather than fixing at STT
or VAD level.
Reason: Deepgram's endpointing runs independently of SileroVAD — Deepgram sends `is_final=True`
results at sentence boundaries regardless of Pipecat's VAD stop_secs setting. Adjusting Deepgram
endpointing params would require API-level configuration and may affect transcription quality.
The NATS bridge is the correct chokepoint: buffer here, join, publish once per conversational turn.
600ms chosen as safe window above Deepgram's typical inter-sentence gap (~200-400ms).

